H O L I D A Y W E I G H T G A I N | ok, so I get asked ‘how do you not put weight on while you’re away’ a lot. And it’s a fair question: when you’re used to a routine (food + fitness) change can be a toughie.
_
Especially if you’ve spent the month before getting in your best shape - that’s body AND mind.
_
First off let’s clear up a myth: you don’t put fat on overnight. Water retention, yes. But fat no. Just because a breakfast was 40% miniature pastries it doesn’t mean your butt will be too. That’s because, it’s what you do regularly that counts not randomly. The moment when I actually believed this was the moment I stopped constantly thinking about treats. Now I eat them when I want (see randomly, not at every meal) then move on.
_
I also exercise 4-5 times a week most weeks of the year. This exercise changes with what my goals are, but always includes some strength (or resistance training) and a cardio element.
_
This means I have a healthy amount of muscle mass and also don’t hate moving my body. Both of these combined mean that when I go away I get stuck into the buffet and also don’t see a cycle to the beach or a long walk as an annoying thing.
_
Holidays by definition are extended periods of leisure and recreation. If to you that means taking a week off exercise so be it. We all need a break from our daily grind so don’t spend your holiday time doing things you begrudge. Who really cares if you do weigh a lbs extra when you land? No one will notice, promise. That said, if you like to keep moving then do. Or, schedule he week before your holiday as your high intensity week so your holiday naturally becomes your de-load or backoff week.
_
Personally I believe you’ve nailed healthy living when you make mindful choices. Sometimes that will be a blueberry brioche because er, delicious. Other times it’s a sunset stroll as you’ve been horizontal on a lounger for the last 8 hours. Such is life.

S A M E  B O D Y,  N E W  R O U T I N E...
_
For 11 years PCOS has been in the background of my life: my body, my fitness, my skin - often they’ve been at the mercy of my hormones.
_
So today’s a new day: I’ve decided to get to grips with my cycle by switching my contraception. NO I’m not planning a baby, but to better understand what’s going on down there I wanted to start a new natural way of preventing pregnancy. Because periods, or lack of, affect my mood, muscle and general well-being. It works for some - not so much for me.
_
For the next 3 months (and hopefully more) it’s wake up, take my temperature using @naturalcyles and only then reach for my phone. 
_
I’m actually quite looking forward to helping to open up the conversation on female health. We shouldn’t feel embarrassed or shame about getting to grips with ovulation, cycles and more. It’s life. Period.
(18+, and NC doesn't protect against STI's)

20 THINGS I LEARNED RUNNING 20 MILES |⠀
1. OK, this is obvious. But 20 miles is very far and therefore you need a route that doesn't involve loads of stopping at traffic lights.⠀
2. Audio books are a great way to take your mind off point one. I listened to Harry Potter inspired by @thefoodmedic. ⠀
3. Drinking coffee pre-run can increase dehydration therefore you need to take on extra water.⠀
4. DO buy trainers 1/2 bigger than you need. This helps save toenails.⠀
5. A good hairband is as essential as point 4. Pulling your pony tight every 6 mins is effing annoying. ⠀
6. Don't wear pants unless you know they won't end up in your butt.⠀
7. GOOD running socks aren't a luxury but a necessity. I wear @lululemonuk or @stancesocks. Think about cost per wear when investing to make yourself feel less sick about their price. ⠀
8. Smile at strangers. It's nice.
9. By mile 10 you'll probably need to fart. Runners stomach is legit a thing. Turn up your music and just keep running. If you can't hear it it didn't happen, right?⠀
10. Not all gels are gross. The coffee @scienceinsport is 100.
11. You will probably choose your furture 🐶 about 33 times. ⠀
12. Instagram can be a nice place when you're bored / lonely – THANK YOU FOR ALL THE NICE STORY comments today guys. ⠀
13. Don't rely soley on technology. If it fails you'll be crushed...definitely not bitter that my watch wasn’t tracked today ⠀
14. And don't trust your watch for calories burned. If it really matters to you wear a heart rate monitor chest strap. ⠀
15. But why calorie count? Long runs are about the acivity and achievement in my book. ⠀
16. Vaseline on your nipples does help⠀
17. Running waistcoats are comfier than a waist belt.

There isn't (or shouldn't be) one definition of 🌴WELLNESS 🌴For me it's doing the things that make me feel content and happy and ultimately well in myself because if I have a happy mind I make healthy decisions. Sometimes this isn't the case and it goes a bit tits up. On those days I say "eff it" and move on. You might wonder why I'm droning on. Well it's

"I don't stress, I do my best"
.
.
Wow, it's so nice to say it and mean every single syllable.
.
.
I've spoken a lot recently about how chasing a future me (or trying to sweat my way there) was actually what was holding me back in life.
.
.
Overtraining and feeling exhausted made me ratty at work. Always feeling hungry and constantly snacking screwed with my eating habits.
.
.
Then there was the stress: not enough to time train, not enough time for emails, not enough time to even pee without being on my phone doing something, anything, productive. .
.
.
Then I stopped. I stopped putting pressure on. I stopped taking the fun out of life and I stopped trying to fit my body to self imposed ideals. Because I'm enough. In fact i'm more than enough, I'm really great.
.
.
SO there you have it. My completely honest statement of why I couldn't be prouder to help bring back @womenshealthuk

1. Half the battle is mental strength. At 6 miles I debated about slowing down. Then I ‘listened to my legs’ (best advice from @twicethehealth at the start line) and realised they were fine. So I pushed on

3. Tailgating a pacer works. So thank you to all the pacers who help people like me hit faster speeds
4. And speed. This is individual... run at your pace. It doesn’t matter what anyone else you know is doing. Run YOUR best for where you are now. So surround yourself with a tribe who support (not compete) with each other (@ces_menato, @becsgentry, @twicethehealth ⚡️). 5. Wear layers that you don’t mind ditching along the way. S E L F D O U B T / L O V E ✨ I've read many a self-help book over the years. In fact, I actually had to put myself on a self help book ban as they were the only things I was reading and I wasn't giving myself the time to process the advice.
_
However, all the words, advice and honesty that I've read has helped me be believe in my beliefs.
_
Just last night I whipped out my new @gabbybernstein message cards in the pub. To my pals, they're nonsense but to me, they're a daily pep-up at my desk. They're so bonkers they provide relief when life gets too serious or my "junk drawer of emotions" is about to overflow. This difference in likes and tastes is one the most important takeaways from my library of wellness literature.
_
It's okay for us all to be into different things. We don't have to like the latest trend or Instagram it because the health agenda suggests so.
_
Tapping into what I really want out of life (helped by learning to meditate) has changed my stress levels, meltdowns and general daily outlook. Oh and how busy my diary is. I really do keep time for me these days.
_
And reading @gabbybernstein books and following/stalking her journey has helped me ditch some aggression and handle things with less drama.

Like diets or nut butters, there isn’t one trainer for everything.⠀
⠀
This message is only going to become more wide spread over the next year.⠀
⠀
But why?⠀
⠀
Well, it’s simple. Talk to an experts and they’ll explain that your feet require different support in different movements. When squatting you need stability. But when running, you’ll often want a trainer that rebounds and helps propel you forward. ⠀
⠀
Think of this way: why would you want your trainer to be tipping you forward when you have a heavy weight or your back? Or, likewise, if you trainer doesn’t flex when running it’s not a natural movement. ⠀
⠀
Normally, it’s the sole that makes all the difference. ⠀
⠀
There are many marketing messages that I chose to ignore, but trainer tech no more.⠀

CALORIE BURN - it needs to be a high as possible right? Well, not necessarily.⠀
Calories are just a measurement of energy. This is why weight loss for most is actually pretty simple: burn more calories than you put in.⠀
_⠀
When you take note of this - and what you’re putting in your body / burning - things can be a lot less stressful. ⠀
_⠀
We don’t have to be trying to lose weight every day (stats show that 2 out of 3 women constantly tried to lose weight last year). It’s OK to not want to lose weight one week to the next next. ⠀
_⠀
You can also use your tracker stats more wisely. Personally I use mine to see how little I move. Often, I’ll only burn 150 calories in the day as I sit at desk all day. This is the same as two caramel digestives.⠀
_⠀
When you know what you’re taking out it makes it a lot easier to judge what you want to put in if keeping things in balance (or wanting a loss) is your plan.⠀
_⠀
Not seeing results is frustrating. Clock in with yourself and your intake / outtake.⠀

On 20.08.16 I made a pact with myself: to spend my 31st year getting into my healthiest shape yet.
_
As I soak up every bit of niceness @thedorchester I actually think I've hit my goal!
-
